  <section>
    <title>Recap: The Axiom of Completeness</title>
<p>We were reminded that <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>, though a beautiful number system (everybody say "ordered field"!), it is literally full of holes.</p>
<p>If we want geometry and algebra to be consistent ("two non-parallel lines intersect at a point") we must fill in the holes!</p>
<p>We do this using the Axiom on Completeness:</p>

     <theorem>
            <title>Axiom of Completeness</title>
            <statement>
                <p>If <m>A</m> is a nonempty set that is bounded above, then it has a least upper bound.</p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>

<p>With this the set of real numbers <m>\mathbb{R}</m> is the set <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> plus all the numbers we created as suprema of all possible sets that are bounded above.</p>

<p>In practice, we will continue working with the real numbers in the way we've learned to work with them except that we're learning more about the reals.  For example, they form a <term>complete</term> ordered field!</p>

</section>

<section>
    <title>Working with Suprema (and Infima)</title>

    <definition>
        <statement>
            Let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be nonempty.  The real number <m>s</m> is a <term>least upper bound</term> (aka <term>supremum</term>) of <m>A</m> if
                <ol>
                    <li><m>s</m> is an upper bound for <m>A</m>, and</li>
                    <li>if <m>M</m> is another upper bound, then <m>s \leq M</m>.</li>
                </ol>
            The real number <m>\ell</m> is a <term>greatest lower bound</term> (aka <term>infimum</term>) of <m>A</m> if
                <ol>
                    <li><m>\ell</m> is an lower bound for <m>A</m>, and</li>
                    <li>if <m>m</m> is another lower bound, then <m>m \leq \ell</m>.</li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
    </definition>

<theorem>
    <statement>
        <p>Let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be a nonempty set that is bounded above.  Let <m>s \in \mathbb{R}</m> be an upper bound for <m>A</m>. Then <m>s=\sup(A)</m> if and only if, for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there is an <m>a \in A</m> with <m>s-\epsilon &lt; a</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    </theorem>

</section>
<section>
    <title>Working with Suprema (and Infima)</title>

    <theorem>
    <statement>
        <p>Let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be a nonempty set that is bonded above.  Let <m>s \in \mathbb{R}</m> be an uppoer bound for <m>A</m>. Then <m>s=\sup(A)</m> if and only if, for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there is an <m>a \in A</m> with <m>s-\epsilon &lt; a</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    </theorem>
        <proof>
            <p>(<m>\Longrightarrow</m>, Contradiction) </p>
            <p>Assume <m>s=\sup(A)</m>.  We must show that for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there is an <m>a \in A</m> with <m>s-\epsilon &lt; a</m>.</p>
            <p>Suppose not.  Suppose the opposite of what we want to conclude is true.  The negation of ``or every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there is an <m>a \in A</m> with <m>s-\epsilon &lt; a</m>'' is ``there is an<m>\epsilon_0 &gt; 0</m> where <m>s-\epsilon_0 \geq a</m> for all <m>a \in A</m>.''</p>
            <p>This assumption implies that <m>s-\epsilon_0</m> is an upper bond for <m>A</m>.  Since <m>s=\sup(A)</m> is the least upper bound for <m>A</m>, it follows that <m>s &lt; s-\epsilon_0</m>.  But this is impossible.</p>
            <p>Therefore, our assumption that there is an<m>\epsilon_0 &gt; 0</m> where <m>s-\epsilon_0 \geq a</m> for all <m>a \in A</m> must be false.  It's opposite must be true.  Therefore, given any <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there exists an <m>a \in A</m> for which <m>s-\epsilon &lt; a</m>.  This completes the proof of this part.</p>

            <p>(<m>\Longleftarrow</m>, Contradiction) </p>
            <p>Let <m>s \in \mathbb{R}</m> be an upper bound for <m>A</m>.  Also assume that for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there is an <m>a \in A</m> with <m>s-\epsilon &lt; a</m>.   We must show that <m>s=\sup(A)</m>.  By definition, this means we must show that (1) <m>s</m> is an upper bound for <m>A</m>, and (2) if <m>M</m> is any other upper bound for <m>A</m> then <m>s \leq M</m>.</p>
            <p>Since we are already assuming the former, we need only prove the latter.</p>
            <p>Let <m>M</m> be another upper bound for <m>A</m>.</p>
            <p>Suppose <m>M &lt; s</m>.  Choose <m>\epsilon_0 = s-M</m> so that <m>M=s-\epsilon_0</m>.</p>
            <p>Since <m>s</m> has the property that, for every <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, there is an <m>a \in A</m> with <m>s-\epsilon &lt; a</m>, we know there is an <m>a_0 \in A</m> for which <m>M=e-\epsilon_0 &lt; a_0</m>.</p>
            <p>But this means that <m>M</m> is not an upper bound for <m>A</m>!  Contradiction.</p>
            <p>Consequently, our supposition that <m>M &lt; s</m> was incorrect.  We conclude that <m>M \grq s</m>.  With this, we have shows that <m>s</m> satisfies the definition of what it means to be the supremum of <m>A</m>.  QED.</p>
        </proof>
    </section>

<section>
    <title>More on Suprema</title>       


    <example>
        <title>Supremum of a subset</title>
        <p>If <m>A_1 \subseteq A_2</m> are sets of real numbers that are both bounded above, then <m>\sup(A_1) \leq \sup(A_2)</m>.</p>
        <p workspace="4.5in"></p>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Supremum of a union</title>
        <p>If <m>A_1</m> and <m>A_2</m> are sets of real numbers that are bounded above, then <md>\sup(A_1 \cup A_2) = \max\{\sup(A_1), \sup(A_2)\}</md>.</p>
        <p workspace="4.5in"></p>
    </example>

<p>Can you come up with a relationship between the suprema of two sets and the suprema of their intersection?  Their infima?</p>

</section>

<section>
    <title>Consequences of Completeness</title>       

<p>Well, you can't to this with the rationals!</p>

<theorem>
    <title>Nested Interval Property</title>
        <statement>
            For each <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>, define <m>I_n=[a_n,b_n] \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> so that <m>I_n \subseteq I_{n-1}</m>.   Then <m>\bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty} I_n \neq \emptyset</m>.
        </statement>
</theorem>

<p>The intervals in this theorem are all closed and bounded intervals of reals that form a sequence of <term>nested intervals</term>. 
<md>I_1 \supseteq I_2 \supseteq I_3 \supseteq \cdots \supseteq I_n \supseteq \cdots</md></p>

<proof>
<p workspace="1in">
    Before we begin, notice how the endpoints of the intervals <m>I_k</m> are related to one another.    
</p>

<p>Since <m>I_1 \subseteq I_k</m> for all <m>k</m>, we know <m>a_k \leq b_1</m> for all <m>k \in \mathbb{N}</m>.  This shows that the set <m>A=\{a_n \, : \, n \in \mathbb{N} \}</m> is bounded above.  Let <m>x=\sup(A)</m>.</p>
<p>Consider some <m>I_n</m>.  We claim that <m>x \in I_n</m>.</p>
<p>Since <m>x</m> is an upper bound for <m>A</m>, we know <m>a_n \leq x</m> for all <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>.</p>
<p>Since <m>b_n</m> is an upper bound for <m>A</m>, and since <m>x</m> is the least upper bound for <m>A</m> we can conclude that <m>x \leq b_n</m>.  This shows <m>x \in I_n</m>.</p>
<p>Since <m>n</m> above was arbitrary, we have shown that <m>x \in I_n</m> for all <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>.</p>
<p>Consequently, <m>x \in \bigcap_{n=1}^{\infty}I_n</m>, as desired.</p>


<figure>
    <caption>A representation of the real line with zero and two real numbers, <m>x &lt; 0 &lt; y</m>.</caption>
